english:
  title: Memorial to Minister Cho, the Grand Commandant
  author: Lee Gyu-bo
  language: eng
  text: "On this day of this month, your humble servant, having purified himself through ritual ablution and fasting, respectfully submits this memorial to the Grand Commandant and Prime Minister, begging the attention of your esteemed office.\n\nIn ancient times, those who became rulers did not find it difficult to govern the realm—rather, they found it difficult to recognize talent and worthlessness in men, to advance or retreat them, to promote or demote them. Why is this? The illustrious sovereign dwells in the innermost chambers of the palace. How could he meet each person individually, test them one by one, discern the worthy from the unworthy, and decide who should advance or retreat? It is only through placing wise ministers as his eyes and ears that this becomes possible. The minister is not one who personally manages trivial matters of taxation, salt monopoly, litigation, and levies. Rather, his responsibility is solely to recommend the talented and advance worthy scholars, thereby assisting the ruler's illuminated wisdom.\n\nToday, the Emperor follows this principle and has placed you in the position of chief counselor. With your vast and brilliant talent for commanding the age, you serve as the Emperor's eyes and ears, holding the destiny of all scholars in your hands, determining their advancement and retreat. Thus, all those who possess rare gifts and exceptional brilliance seek to offer themselves to you like precious jade and treasures beyond price.\n\nOne such as myself is but a foolish and worthless man, possessing neither talent nor skill worthy of promotion by a wise lord and enlightened minister. By reason, I should measure my station, restrain my ambitions, and not dare to hope for a place among those of exceptional merit. Yet you, not knowing my unworthiness, have favored my empty reputation with great kindness. Once you joined with the three ministers and the two officials of the highest rank in submitting a memorial recommending me for appointment to a provincial post, requesting that this become a step toward my future advancement. The imperial edict was granted, but before it could be forwarded to the Ministry of Personnel, it suddenly vanished like a silver cup that sprouted wings. The court and the literati all knew of this, and many voiced their astonishment and confusion. Your esteemed office doubtless heard of it as well.\n\nRelying on your strength and determination, I believed the matter already settled. How could I betray the weight of one word merely because an edict appeared or disappeared? Thus I was confident in my prospects. Yet after the new administration took office, nothing was heard, and my joy turned to tears. My peers ridiculed me, and my face burned with shame and embarrassment.\n\nLater, I heard that you explained the matter by saying the edict had not been filed with the Ministry of Personnel. This is hardly an urgent defense on my behalf. Why need you make such excuses? If you desire to appoint me directly to the capital without provincial service, this would be without precedent and would require imperial sanction. But if it is a provincial post you wish to grant, then by the established rules of the realm, all successful examination candidates may be appointed to provincial service without age restrictions. In former times, those of merit received such posts immediately, and the rest obtained them within three or four years at most.\n\nHowever, in recent times many officials have advanced rapidly, yet provincial positions have not increased accordingly. Thus those who wait patiently remain blocked and delayed—some have waited thirty years, even twenty-eight or twenty-nine, without advancement. Should I follow in their footsteps, patiently waiting my turn, I would grow white-haired without assurance of appointment.\n\nSince you do not treat me as an ordinary man but wish to reward my diligent scholarship, then surpass those who came before me in merit. That age should be a barrier is not the law of the realm. Though I do not require an imperial edict, neither would it violate state law. Moreover, the edict has already been granted—why hide it away? \n\nAlas, what the minister recommends cannot be taken lightly. Nor is there but one minister whose recommendations are rooted in the principle of recommending one worthy man to encourage a hundred. These are not shallow intentions. If the Emperor had refused, that would be one matter. But having already consented, to then find obstacles in between would be the fault of those charged with executing his will—surely they bear the blame.\n\nWith your authority as chief among all officials, your power is sufficient to investigate and impeach any corruption in the court. You should seize this moment to demand why the memorial was withheld and press charges against those responsible. Yet if you dare not do this, how can the court's discipline be restored? How can the Emperor's vision be broadened? How can talented men advance? On your behalf, I lament this state of affairs.\n\nOnce, someone asked a stable master: \"How much does your horse eat in a day?\" The master replied: \"I provide a certain measure of grain.\" \"Then why is the horse so thin?\" asked the man. \"I merely promised,\" said the master, \"but gave nothing.\" Such is my plight—truly I hunger and grow thin. Can you bear not to look upon me and complete your benefaction?\n\nThough I am unworthy, throughout my life I have held only to sincerity and integrity. All that I have gathered in my heart, I now lay bare before you. Though this may seem self-praise, I conceal nothing and shrink from no judgment.\n\nI have read since the age of nine and have not let books leave my hands. From the Poetry and History, the Six Classics, the philosophers, histories, and writings, to the obscure scriptures, rare texts, Buddhist sutras, and Daoist teachings—though I have not penetrated their deepest mysteries, I have surveyed and absorbed them, selecting their finest passages as tools for elegant expression.\n\nLikewise, from Fuxi onward through the Three Dynasties, Han, Qin, Jin, Sui, Tang, and Five Dynasties, I have studied the successes and failures of rulers and ministers, the order and chaos of nations, and the rise and fall of loyal servants, traitors, and great thieves. Though I have not compiled all such records exhaustively, I have distilled their essence, memorized key lessons, and prepared myself to respond aptly to the needs of the moment.\n\nWhen I take brush to paper to compose on wind and moon, though my verses reach a hundred rhymes and span great themes, my writing flows without pause. Though I may not equal works embroidered in golden thread and studded with pearls, neither do I fail the standards of poetry.\n\nYet what is the use? My talents will rot with the grass and trees. I hope only to grasp the vermillion brush, pass through the golden gates, ascend to the Jade Hall, serve as the Emperor's voice, draft his edicts and proclamations, and spread his will throughout the realm. Only thus would my lifetime's ambition be fulfilled. I do not seek mere pittance to feed my wife and children.\n\nAlas, though my aspirations are great, my talents are meager. Heaven has dealt me a narrow fate. Now thirty years old, I have yet to hold even a provincial post. My circumstances are most pitiable—yet my head knows its own measure. My fortune rises and falls with your judgment. My advancement depends upon your recognition. What more can I say?\n\nShould you show me but a moment's favor and open a path for me, granting me a first step in office, then across ten thousand miles of blue sky I might soar aloft. Why then should I fear that the road is long and the day grows late? Moreover, when a scholar seeks the favor of princes and great men, it is not merely for his own sake—it is to honor them as well. If, knocking once and twice, I receive no answer, still I cannot lightly depart, for I owe it to the state, to you, and to my own honor to persevere. Perhaps in time I may prove worthy of a humble scholar's reputation.\n\nYet if, knocking a third time, I still receive no answer, I am by nature too proud for such daily opportunism. Rather, I would withdraw to remote mountains and live contentedly among deer in forests thick with grass—I could not bring myself to stand at your gate again like a beggar at a dog hole or stable door, soiled by dust and refuse.\n\nMengzi taught: \"All men desire office, yet those who pursue it by improper means are like thieves who tunnel beneath walls.\" I have already been too forward in promoting myself—can I descend further to such shameless theft?\n\nThis letter, born of disappointment, speaks with too much heat. I beg you to first forgive my offenses, then consider my plea. I tremble at having ventured to trouble your great dignity. I can say no more.\n\nYour servant bows twice in reverence."
